        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e1ca6747739ddfc6",
        "text": "Systems lack the \"[[Requisite Variety]]\" (Ashby) that would be necessary to respond to any state of the environment or to set up the environment in a way that is exactly appropriate to the system. There is, in other words, no point-by-point correspondence between system and environment (a condition which, moreover, would cancel the difference of system and environment). For this very reason, it becomes a problem to establish and maintain this difference in spite of a complexity inferiority. The complexity inferiority must be compensated by selection strategies. That the system is forced to selection results already from its own complexity. Which order is chosen in the relation of its elements results from the complexity difference to the environment. Both aspects can be broken down analytically in this way. However, they form only two sides of one and the same circumstance, because only by selection of an order a system can be complex. (Luhmann, Soziale Systeme, 47–48)"
      },
      "attribution": {
        "page": "2023-03-08"
      },
